title: Library Contract Request: ProQuest Ebook Central (Middlesex County College)

communications.subject: New Jersey Open Public Records Act Request: Library Contract Request: ProQuest Ebook Central (Middlesex County College)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Jersey Open Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

The most recent contract, governing, base, or master license agreement with Clarivate / ProQuest relating to the licensing of ProQuest Ebook Central;
All related terms and conditions, terms of service, amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, and/or letters of intent; and
All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the contractual relations with Clarivate / ProQuest for ebook licensing. 

Responsive materials include all contracts, agreements, amendments, appendices, invoices, and any other documents listed above that incorporate language governing terms of use of ProQuest Ebook Central.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

smhc

Responsive emails may include the key words "Twitter", "Twitter.com", "tweet" and "graphics".

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Dave Hendricks

communications.subject: FOIA Request, CBP-2018-083302
communications.communication:
Dave Hendricks 
MuckRock News, 411A Highland Ave DEPT MR 60057 Somerville MA 02144 
10/31/2018 
CBP-2018-083302 
Dear Dave Hendricks: 
This automated notice acknowledges receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) received on 08/29/2018 requesting all email sent or received by U.S. Border Patrol El Paso Sector Chief Patrol Agent Aaron A. Hull from Jan. 1 to Aug. 28, 2018, relating or referring to Twitter including the key words "Twitter", "Twitter.com", "tweet" and "graphics". 
Please use the following unique FOIA tracking number CBP-2018-083302 to track the status of your request.  If you have not already done so, you must create a FOIAonline account at https://foiaonline.gov.  This is the only method available to check the status of your pending FOIA request. (https://foiaonline.regulations.gov/) 
Provisions of the Act allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS FOIA regulations outlined on the DHS website, https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2016/11/22/2016-28095/freedom-of-information-act-regulations. By submitting your request, you have agreed to pay up to $25.00 in applicable processing fees, if any fees associated with your request exceed this amount, CBP shall contact you; however, the first 100 pages are free. (https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2016/11/22/2016-28095/freedom-of-information-act-regulations) 
Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request.  Consistent with 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, CBP processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt.  Although CBP’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period in certain circumstances pursuant to 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(c). 
For additional information please consult CBP FOIA website please click on FOIA Act Resources or visit (http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia) http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia. (http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia) 
Sincerely, 
U.S. Customs and Border Protection

CBP-2018-083302 

Dear Dave Hendricks, 

This is just a short note to inform you of the status of your request.  Please see the bullet checked below for information regarding your request to U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP): 

[ ] We are still conducting searches for records which may be responsive to your request. 

[ ]  The custodians most likely to hold your records have been identified and your request has been tasked for search.  Once the volume of documents has been determined, we will reach out to better target your request so we may process it in the most efficient and expeditious manner possible. 

[x ]  Records responsive to your request have been identified and we are currently conducting our review.  You will be notified when your records are ready for release. 

[ ]  We would like to update you that your request has moved to the next stage in processing and records are currently being reviewed by our component offices. We anticipate that the records will be ready for release shortly. You will be notified via email when your records are available for viewing. 

Although CBP is working hard to reduce our backlog, if your request included a search for emails, please be advised that requests of this type are typically taking 12 to 24 months to process.  Thank you for your patience while we continue to work on reducing our backlog. 

If you wish to discuss your request in more detail, or at any time you wish to withdraw your request, please call our Public Liaison at 202-325-0150 and reference your request number. 

Please note that this message has been sent from an unmonitored e-mail account. Any messages sent to this account will not be read. 

Sincerely, 

U.S. Customs and Border Protection

title: ALPR Audit Reports Review by Chief of Police Schenita Stewart

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: ALPR Audit Reports Review by Chief of Police Schenita Stewart
communications.communication:
Subject: ALPR Audit Reports Review by Chief of Police Schenita Stewart

Dear FOIA Officer,

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request records related to the Evanston Police Department’s (EPD) use of Flock Safety automated license plate reader (ALPR) technology. This request is based on a recent communication from Schenita Stewart, Chief of Police regarding state surveillance and Evanston’s Welcoming City Ordinance:

“To ensure compliance with the Welcoming City Ordinance and protect community trust, I have assigned a dedicated supervisor to oversee all aspects of ALPR usage within EPD. Furthermore, we conduct regular organizational and network audits, which I personally review. EPD also operates under a clear and established policy governing ALPR use, reinforcing both accountability and transparency.”

According to the City of Evanston's website page on the "Welcoming City Ordinance" (Ordinance 17-O-25):

"Key updates to the Ordinance include:

Data Protection: Prohibiting the sharing of city databases or information with federal immigration agencies, or with third parties unless they certify against its use for civil immigration enforcement.

Expanded Safeguards: Clarifying that City officials will not participate in civil immigration enforcement by any agency or personnel, including private contractors. The City will continue to comply with a valid criminal warrant.

Closing Loopholes: Strengthening policies to eliminate exceptions that previously allowed limited City involvement in immigration enforcement under certain conditions.

Support for Immigrants: Codifying practices that assist crime victims in obtaining specific visas and providing immigration resource information through public services like 311.

Safe Public Buildings: The City is now tasked with developing policies for its public facilities that prioritize limiting immigration enforcement operations on their premises to the fullest extent allowed by law."

In light of this statement made by Schenita Stewart, Chief of Police, along with the updates to Evanston's Welcoming City Ordinance, and in accordance with Illinois law (625 ILCS 5/2-130), which prohibits sharing automated license plate reader ALPR data with out-of-state agencies for purposes such as interfering with reproductive health access or enforcing immigration laws, I request full transparency for the following:

1) Any records showing review or oversight of Flock Safety automated license plate reader ALPR Organization or Network audit reports by the Chief of Police Schenita Stewart from January 1, 2024, to the present - including emails, memos, meeting notes, audit summaries, annotations, or briefings demonstrating the Stewart’s direct involvement in reviewing audit data.

2) Any communications between the Chief of Police Schenita Stewart and Evanston Police Department supervisors or Flock Safety automated license plate reader ALPR administrators regarding network audit findings that raised questions or concerns, including but not limited to:
    a) Access by out-of-state agencies (e.g., AL, FL, IN, KY, MO, NC, TX, etc) 
    b) Federal agency involvement (e.g., DHS, HSI, ICE, CBP, etc)
    c) References to abortion or reproductive health care (e.g., abortion, women, woman, pregnant, pp, planned parenthood, etc)
    d) References to immigration enforcement (e.g., immigration, border patrol, 287g, etc)
    e) Search reasons lacking case numbers or specific descriptions (e.g., inv, p, m, zz, training, test, ab501, invest, narcotics, drugs, 123abv, etc)

3) Any internal protocols or policies that describe the role of the Evanston Police Department’s chief or supervisors in reviewing Flock Safety automated license plate reader ALPR audits and identifying potentially inappropriate use, particularly regarding compliance with Illinois statutes and Evanston’s Welcoming City Ordinance.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Niles Coalition

communications.subject: RE: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request #25-1704
communications.communication:
Hello, as a requester under the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (5 ILCS 140), I remind you of the following:

- Under 5 ILCS 140/3(d), a public body must respond to a FOIA request within 5 business days.
- Under 5 ILCS 140/3(e), a one-time extension of no more than 5 additional business days is permitted, provided proper notice is given.

After that, any additional delay requires the requester's consent. I only agreed to a single extension on June 17, 2025, setting a revised overdue deadline of June 23, 2025.
Subsequent extensions requested on:

- June 26, 2025
- July 7, 2025

were not consented to, and therefore violate the requirements of the Illinois FOIA statute.

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Palos Heights PD Immigration Enforcement
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

On 1/28/2025 between 1:28pm and 5:35 at least 11 ALPR queries were run by Palos Heights Police Department relating to immigration violations, looking for vehicle license plates in both Illinois and nationally across the United States. The queries include the following plates: "3376532B" "ES53782" and "CF49166". 

Please provide the following documents relating to these queries:
1) Police reports, investigative files, and case notes for the cases involving these queries. 
2) Any policies, procedures, SOPs, or internal memos from Palos Heights PD regarding working on immigration cases and cooperation with ICE. 
3) If the query was run as part of a taskforce assignment, please provide any post orders or other designations (letter of assignment, email stating they are assigned to that taskforce, etc.) that indicate the individual was assigned to the taskforce at that time.    

Thank you in advance for your time and response to this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Abe Segal

communications.subject: FOIA Request
communications.communication:
Good afternoon Abe,

In regards to your FOIA request regarding the task force queries:

1) Police reports, investigative files, and case notes for the cases involving these queries.
The Palos Heights Police Department does not have any records or files in relation to the case involving the Flock inquiries mentioned.

2) Any policies, procedures, SOPs, or internal memos from Palos Heights PD regarding working on immigration cases and cooperation with ICE.
The Palos Heights Police Department does not work on immigration cases and we do not contact ICE, or anyone else, when a subject is found to have an immigration detainer.  Attached are emails forwarded to officers, containing guidance to not honor detainers if received and the Immigration Law Guidance to Law Enforcement sent out by the Illinois Attorney General.  None of our officers are cross-designated with any immigration authority.

3) If the query was run as part of a taskforce assignment, please provide any post orders or other designations (letter of assignment, email stating they are assigned to that taskforce, etc.) that indicate the individual was assigned to the taskforce at that time.
Our investigation into this matter has revealed that while these inquiries appear to have been run as part of a taskforce assignment, no member of the Palos Heights Police Department "ran" those queries.  They were, apparently, run by another, non-Palos Heights, task force member who used a  Palos Height's member's sign in and password information without his knowledge.


If you have any questions, please let me know.
Thank you,
Morgan Pukula
Palos Heights Police Department
7607 W College Drive
Palos Heights, IL 60463

communications.subject: RE: Texas Public Information Act Request: Academic Dishonesty Study (University Of Houston); IR10498
communications.communication:
Requestor, my office received your request below. You have asked for “a spreadsheet containing all the academic dishonesty reports from the beginning of the Fall 2021 semester to the end of the Spring 2025 Semester, organized by university college.”

In accordance with Texas Government Code § 552.222, the University seeks clarification regarding your request. You ask for information concerning all academic dishonesty reports by college for a 4 year period. Academic dishonesty information that includes personally identifiable information about a student is protected from disclosure by the federal law FERPA. Please clarify whether you are seeking information about the number of reports only. If not, please explain what you are seeking.  Please note that the University cannot provide student record information in response to a Public Information Act request.
Please simply respond to this e-mail to provide clarification.  The University is required to inform you that if you fail to respond to this e-mail seeking to clarify your request within 61 days, your request will be considered withdrawn. Regards, Jennifer Bloom
____________________________________

title: New Mexico IPRA Request: Police disciplinary files for officers/deputies in Sixth Judicial District

communications.subject: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: New Mexico IPRA Request: Police disciplinary files for officers/deputies in Sixth Judicial District
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.

- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joshua Bowling

communications.subject: Michigan Freedom of Information Act Request: Library Contract Request: HeinOnline database (Michigan State University) (Michigan State University)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Michigan Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) The most recent contract, governing, base, or master license agreement with William S. Hein & Co. relating to the licensing of the “HeinOnline” database;
2) All related terms and conditions, terms of service, amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, and/or letters of intent; and
3) All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the contractual relations with William S. Hein & Co. for the “HeinOnline” database. 

Please do not limit your search to strictly direct agreements or renewals between the institution and William S. Hein & Co., but include any agreements and related documentation through consortia such as the Midwest Collaborative for Library Services (MCLS), the Big Ten Academic Alliance (BTAA), or Lyrasis.

Responsive materials include all contracts, agreements, amendments, appendices, invoices, and any other documents listed above that incorporate language governing terms of use of the “HeinOnline” database.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ellen Dubinsky

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Cybercheck communications and agreements
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) All contracts, licenses, MOUs, MOAs, data agreements, letters of intent, State of Work documents, Scope of Work documents, and other agreement documents since Jan. 1, 2024 between the Georgia Bureau of Investigation and Global Intelligence Inc. (also called Cybercheck or Cybercheck.AI) for the provision of the Cybercheck service (excluding any already undisclosed via previous FOIAs).

2) All email exchanges, including attachments, between Georgia Bureau of Investigation staff and email addresses with the domain "@cybercheck.ai" between Jan. 1, 2024 and the present (excluding any already undisclosed via previous FOIAs).

3) All email exchanges, including attachments, between Georgia Bureau of Investigation staff making reference to the tool Cybercheck and/or its provider Global Intelligence, sent between Jan. 1, 2023 and the present. 

I kindly request that you waive all fees as I am a journalist and the requested records will be used for journalism in the public interest.

If you choose to impose fees, I request a detailed breakdown of the fees, including the hourly wage of each employee involved and an explanation of the employee hours required to fulfil the request.

If you choose to reject this request or redact portions of responsive documents, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jessica Hatcher

communications.communication:
Dear Valued Customer: 
 
We are in receipt of your public records request for To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

- all record retention schedules
- master list of forms

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Sincerely,

Chris Amico

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Inspector General closed cases 2016 (Defense Intelligence Agency, Office of the Inspector General)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

a copy of the list or printout or database listing of Inspector General investigations closed/reports completed during calendar year 2016. If the list is organized by FY rather than calendar year, the FY 2016 list is sufficient for this request. If no central list or database exists, then I request that the equivalent information be provided in the form of copies of the cover sheet or first page of each IG report completed during calendar year 2016.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emma Best

title: Request on Political Appointees (U.S. Department Of Agriculture)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request on Political Appointees (U.S. Department Of Agriculture)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act. I hereby request the following records:

1. A list of any and all political appointments at the agency appointed from January 20, 2025 until the date of your final response to this request.

2. Copies of resumes for any and all political appointees hired since January 20, 2025 until the date of your final response to this request. These records are likely in the possession of the Designated Agency Ethics Official (DAEO).

Please provide these records as available on a rolling basis.

Documented is an investigative watchdog and reporting group that explores the relationship between special interests and government. This request is likely to contribute significantly to the public’s understanding of the operations of the government. Disclosure of the requested records serves the public interest, and this request is not being made for any commercial purposes. Therefore, I am requesting a waiver of any fees. If you do not grant my fee waiver request, please notify me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request be filled electronically by email attachment or other electronic file transfer if available, or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter.  I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Nina

communications.subject: 2025-OSEC-08250-F FOIA Request Acknowledgement
communications.communication:
Dear Nina Wang:

This email acknowledges receipt of your attached Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to the U.S. Department of Agriculture's (USDA), Office of Information Affairs, FOIA Division (OIA-FOIA). Your request was received by this office on July 7, 2025.

The OIA-FOIA is under the purview of the General Counsel (GC) and serves as the focal point for USDA's FOIA program. It provides coordination and ensures agency-wide compliance with the FOIA.  Additionally, the OIA-FOIA processes requests and appeals on behalf of the Office of the Secretary (OSEC); the Under Secretaries; USDA's staff offices; and the Research, Education and Economics and Trade and Foreign Agricultural Affairs mission areas.

The FOIA, 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(A)(i), requires USDA to make a determination in response to a FOIA request within 20 business days from its date of receipt. In unusual circumstances, the Federal agency time limit may be extended by 10 business days as stated in 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If your request seeks numerous records that will necessitate a wide-ranging search, including searches with components and possible consultations with components that have a substantial interest in the determination of this request, USDA will invoke a 10 business day extension for determination of your request. You have the option to narrow the scope of your request to limit the number of potentially responsive records.

Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Pursuant to USDA FOIA Regulations, Title 7 CFR §1.6(a), the USDA processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt.

Provisions of the FOIA allow USDA to recover part of the cost of complying with your request. For purposes of fee assessment, you have been categorized as a "news media" requester,
pursuant to 7 CFR Appendix A to Subpart A of Part 1 Section 2(b)(4)(i). For your review and information, a copy of the USDA FOIA Fee Schedule is attached. In accordance with 7 CFR Appendix A to Subpart A of Part 1, Section 3(b), your fees shall be waived where the amount of the fee is $25.00 or less.

You have requested a fee waiver.  Your fee waiver request is under consideration.

A search will be conducted for records responsive to your request. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that a FOIA analyst will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request.

Your request has been assigned FOIA Case No. 2025-OSEC-08250-F. Please refer to this case number in any future correspondence. If you have any questions regarding the processing of this request, please contact Susan Ruppel at 202-690-5220 or electronically at susan.ruppel@usda.gov<mailto:susan.ruppel@usda.gov> or USDAFOIA@usda.gov<mailto:USDAFOIA@usda.gov>.

For additional information regarding USDA FOIA regulations and process, please refer to the information available on-line at Freedom of Information Act Division | USDA.<https://www.usda.gov/ogc/office-information-affairs/foia-division>

We appreciate the opportunity to assist you.

Sincerely,

Office of Information Affairs
Freedom of Information Act Division


Susan Ruppel, Esq.
FOIA Analyst
Office of Information Affairs (OIA)

[cid:image001.png@01DBEF4C.09875A60]
Office of the General Counsel (OGC)
1400 Independence Avenue, S.W., Washington, DC, 20250
P:  202-690-5220





This electronic message contains information generated by the USDA solely for the intended recipients. Any unauthorized interception of this message or the use or disclosure of the information it contains may violate the law and subject the violator to civil or criminal penalties. If you believe you have received this message in error, please notify the sender and delete the email immediately.

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: EOCO Reports
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

1. Any/all EOCO complaints filed and ensuing investigatory paperwork from July 1, 2024 - June 30, 2025 for the following schools:

a. Holden Elementary
b. Wildwood Elementary
c. Pulaski Elementary
d. Payton High School
e. Marshall High School

The July 1, 2024 date is meant to be the starting point for reviewing complaints not meant for complaints in progress on July 1, 2024. 

This request is made on behalf of The FOIA Bakery. Because this request is in the public interest for Illinois nonprofit The FOIA Bakery’s work to advocate for public education, please waive any fees in accordance with 5 ILCS § 140/6(c). Feel free to contact me with any questions, or if clarification is needed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Miriam Bhimani

communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
August 4, 2025 Miriam Bhimani 
RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N017936-072025 
Dear Miriam Bhimani: This letter is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request seeking the following information: 
1. Any/all EOCO complaints filed and ensuing investigatory paperwork from July 1, 2024 - June 30, 2025 for the following schools: 
a. Holden Elementary 
b. Wildwood Elementary 
c. Pulaski Elementary 
d. Payton High School 
e. Marshall High School 
The July 1, 2024 date is meant to be the starting point for reviewing complaints not meant for complaints in progress on July 1, 2024. RESPONSE: Records responsive to your FOIA request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center. Please visit the link and enter your username and password to access the records. http://cps.edu/About_CPS/Departments/Law/Pages/FOIARequest.aspx . No EOCO matters were found for Holden ES or Wildwood Elementary.

 206427

 MARSHALL HS  
 Open Be advised that records have been withheld pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(f) exempts any “Preliminary drafts, notes, recommendations, memoranda and other records in which opinions are expressed, or policies or actions are formulated, except that a specific record or relevant portion of a record shall not be exempt when the record is publicly cited and identified by the head of the public body.” Records have been redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(b), “Private information, unless disclosure is required by another provision of this Act, a State or federal law or a court order,” and pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(c), “Personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subjects of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs the legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. The disclosure of information that bears on the public duties of public employees and officials shall not be considered an invasion of personal privacy. Portions of the information you seek are exempt from disclosure pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act, section 7.5(r) exempts from inspection or copying information prohibited from being disclosed by the Illinois Student Records Act (ISSRA). ISSRA prohibits the disclosure of “school student records” and defines a “school student record” as “any writing or other recorded information concerning a student and by which a student may be individually identified, maintained by a school or at its direction or by an employee of a school, regardless of how or where the information is stored. 105 ILCS 10/2(d): Release of a minor’s record may only be authorized by the parent or guardian in accordance with the Illinois Student Records Act (105 ILCS 10/1 et seq.). Additionally, guidance provided by 5 ILCS 7(1)(d)(iv) exempts information that would “unavoidably disclose the identity of a confidential source, confidential information furnished only by the confidential source, or persons who file complaints with or provide information to administrative, investigative, law enforcement, or penal agencies; except that the identities of witnesses to traffic crashes, traffic crash reports, and rescue reports shall be provided by agencies of local government, except when disclosure would interfere with an active criminal investigation conducted by the agency that is the recipient of the request. To the extent you consider this a denial, pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a) you may file a Request for Review with the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at: Public Access Counselor; Office of the Attorney General; 500 South 2nd Street; Springfield, IL 62706.  You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court; 5 ILCS 140/11. If you have any questions, please contact our office at (773) 553-3500. Thank you for your request. Sincerely, Ana Diaz Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

Thanks for your help, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

Good afternoon, 

Please accept this email transmission as fulfillment of your public records request. We understand that you are requesting the following public  information: 
"I would like a spreadsheet containing all the academic dishonesty reports from the beginning of the Fall 2021 semester to the end of the Spring 2025 Semester, organized by university college."
 
In complying with this request, please see the attached document when reviewing this information please consider the custodian's commetns which are provided below.
______________________________________________________
"It is important to note that these are reports and do not reflect outcomes. So Arts and Humanities had 38 reports of dishonesty but that does not mean that 38 individuals were found responsible of dishonesty. I am merrily giving you the number of reports that were submitted.
Important to note that Natural and Social Sciences is the largest college, followed by Arts and Humanities, then School of Business and then School of Education (largest meaning overall enrollment of students). 

Let me know if you need more information. Academic dishonesty/Misconduct covers a variety of charges (plagiarism, cheating, etc.) based on the request I am just giving anything that falls under the umbrella of academic dishonesty (which is all academic misconduct).

I have divided the colleges by Current system effective July 1, 2025. The Unknown are cases where allegations of academic misconduct were made but no information about who did it was included in the report. An example is someone in my class was cheating but I don't know who they are the and the report writer didn't include class information. "
_________________________________________________________
 I apologize for the delay as I was out sick last week. We try not to charge for quick report information. SOU now considers this request fulfilled, please let me know if you have any questions or concerns.   

Have a beautiful day!

On-scene investigation

Thank you for your time and transparency.

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Recruitment and Hiring (Alameda County Sheriff's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting records related to the department's efforts to recruit and hire new officers:
Records include digital and physical, released in their native forms (Excel, PDF, etc)

- ad purchases
- contracts with vendors for ad placement, recruitment and hiring 
- market research and data, if collected
- brand and department strategies created by ad agencies or internally
- data related to applications, KPIs of recruitment and hiring campaigns
- PowerPoint or equivalent presentations, including accompanying documents related to recruitment, hiring, and marketing strategies
- Budgets for recruitment and hiring internally, and the total money spent 
- Pay bonuses or financial incentives to retain officers
- Data by year on the number of officers, sworn and non-sworn

Search from 2021 to today's date.
Please provide in rolling production

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

Alameda County - Sheriff, CA ************************************************************************ A document has been released for record request #25-281 along with the following message: Pursuant to California Government Code Section 7922.535, we write in response to the inquiry that you made to the Alameda County Sheriff’s Office under the California Public Records Act. We note that the requests are limited only to records in our custody and control. Included you will find the information related to your request. In compliance with the California Public Records Act, the document has been redacted pursuant to Cal. Gov. Code §§ 7923.600-7923.625, 7923.805, 7927.700, 7927.700 and 7922.000. * Redacted.zip Document links are valid for one month. Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at Alameda County - Sheriff, CA.

Technical support: See our help page

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: USCIS MPP NRI Pass rate
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any record showing the pass/fail rate for interviews conducted by USCIS Asylum Officers or DHS personnel acting under their supervision in the re-activated version of Remain in Mexico (Migrant Protection Protocols). These records include, but are not limited to, NRIs. 

Because these data will reveal the degree to which USCIS and DHS are affording protection for migrants and refugees consistently with U.S. and international law, because the consequences of failing to do so involve documented risks of kidnapping, extortion, rape, and murder, and because the re-initiation of MPP has been the subject of widespread and extraordinary media interest, I respectfully request expedited processing of this request pursuant to 6 C.F.R. 5.5.(e). 

I make this request on behalf the #DetentionKills Transparency Initiative of Al Otro Lado.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Free

title: Adams County Detention Center CFI Statistics

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Adams County Detention Center CFI Statistics
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Spreadsheets of other records reflecting the numbers of fear establish and fear not established for credible fear interviews decided by the Houston Asylum for individuals detained at Adams County Detention Center since the beginning of Fiscal Year 2020. Please categorize on any spreadsheet by month and/or country of nationality if possible.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Al Otro Lado

title: Texas Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Johnson County Sheriff)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Johnson County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the department’s Flock Safety system:
1. Organization Audit in Flock. 
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Organization Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches done within the agency.

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.

3. A list of network share settings that include:
3a. Flock networks shared with me
3b. Networks that I’m sharing

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Tepper

title: Arkansas Division of Correction Open Record Request - Quattrone Center

communications.subject: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act Request: Arkansas Division of Correction Open Record Request - Quattrone Center
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arkansas Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Arkansas Division of Correction,

Dear Arkansas Division of Correction,

Pursuant to Arkansas freedom of Information Act Request (Ark. Code Ann. § 25-19-101, et seq.) I am requesting access to all records related to the purchase of field drug testing supplies and technologies (used to identify unknown substances that are potentially contraband) by your agency from January 1, 2016 to the present. 

1.	Specifically, I am requesting contracts your agency or department has with providers of drug testing kit or device providers (such as colorimetric or presumptive field tests or testing insurance), or any other records indicating the quantity, cost, vendor, and model of each item or system purchased. This request includes materials related to but not limited to the following:
o	Colorimetric or presumptive field test kits, such as: 
	NIK Public Safety kits 
	Sirchie NARK II kits
	Field Forensics DABIT kits
	Mistral drug identification/detection kits
	M.M.C. International B.V. presumptive drug tests
	TN Scientific Mandelin Reagent drug testing kits
	Macherey-Nagel MEDI-TEST
	Any other colorimetric or presumptive kits
o	Instrument-based technologies, including: 
	Raman spectroscopy devices
	Infrared (IR) spectroscopy devices
	Ion mobility spectrometry (IMS) devices
	Mass spectrometry (MS) devices
	Any other field-portable drug identification technologies
1.	Total annual budget allocated to the purchase or acquisition of such drug testing kits or devices.
2.	Spending information (such as invoices, purchase orders, or receipts) for any presumptive drug testing kits or devices.
3.	This request does not include urine, blood, or other tests designed to identify drug compounds in the human body. This request is made as part of an academic research project examining the use and cost of field drug testing technologies by law enforcement and correctional agencies nationwide. If possible, I request that the records be provided in electronic format (PDF, Excel, or CSV).

If any part of this request is denied, please provide a written explanation for the denial, including the specific exemption(s) relied upon. If the requested records are available in part, I request access to all segregable portions. Should there be any material cost (defined as more than $100) associated with providing the requested information, please provide me with an estimate before proceeding with any work.

Please contact me at QuattroneResearch@law.upenn.edu or 215-746-1251 if you have any questions or require clarification. Thank you for your time and assistance.

Sincerely,

 
Ross Miller
Assistant Director
Quattrone Center for the Fair Administration of Justice

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sonny Albarado, a citizen of Arkansas, in coordination with Ross Miller.

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

[cid:image001.png@01D9C623.0D3F7D80]

communications.subject: ATTORNEY CLIENT PRIVILEGED - RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee



[cid:image002.png@01DA121F.C2136CB0]

As discussed in our letter of December 6, 2023, we are providing the records we currently have available in response to your June 16, 2023, request.  They are located at the website below:

MuckRock - Julia Rock<https://nmgov-my.sharepoint.com/:f:/r/personal/renee_garcia_erb_nm_gov/Documents/MuckRock%20-%20Julia%20Rock?csf=1&web=1&e=4gwfSH>

As also discussed, we will require additional time to provide the remainder of the records.  We plan to provide additional documents on or before February 1, 2024.  Thank you again for your continued patience regarding this matter.
Regards,
Renee

communications.subject: Delaware Freedom of Information Act Request: Library Contract Request: EBSCO Education Research Complete (Delaware State University)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Delaware Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The most recent contract, governing, base, or master license agreement with EBSCO relating to the licensing of Education Research Complete;
All related terms and conditions, terms of service, amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, and/or letters of intent; and
All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the contractual relations with EBSCO for Education Research Complete database licensing. 

Responsive materials include all contracts, agreements, amendments, appendices, invoices, and any other documents listed above that incorporate language governing terms of use of Education Research Complete.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jonathan Rudenberg, a citizen of Delaware, in coordination with smhc.

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Jaspar Singh, who died in ICE Custody April 15, 2024, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddrSinghJaspar.pdf

I make this request as a member of the media, and therefore seek a fee waiver. Representative edited works based on prior FOIA requests like this one may be reviewed here: https://theappeal.org/authors/andrew-free/; and here: https://atlpresscollective.com/2025/01/31/new-record-sheds-light-on-unreported-death-in-atlanta-airport-customs-inspection/. 

I request expedited processing of this request pursuant to 6 CFR 5.5(e) and attest under penalty of perjury pursuant to 28 USC 1746 that the following statements are true and correct to the best of my knowledge and understanding: 
1. ICE deaths in custody in FY25 are currently on track to equal or surpass the 12 deaths in the previous fiscal year. 

2. IHSC Mortality Reviews provide an authoritative agency accounting of the medical circumstances of in-custody deaths. These reviews often conflict with the public-facing story the agency tells, raising critical questions about accountability, transparency, waste, fraud, and abuse. See https://phr.org/our-work/resources/deadly-failures-preventable-deaths-in-u-s-immigration-detention/.

communications.subject: ICE FOIA 2025-ICFO-25068
communications.communication:
03/13/2025 

Andrew  Free 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR182995 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2025-ICFO-25068 
 
Dear Requester: 

This acknowledges receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), dated 3/13/2025, your request for a waiver of all assessable FOIA fees, and your request for expedited treatment. Your request was received in this office on 3/13/2025. Specifically, you have requested records pertaining to a copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Jaspar Singh, who died in ICE Custody April 15, 2024, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddrSinghJaspar.pdf. 

Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. 

Your request for expedited treatment is hereby denied. 

Under the DHS FOIA regulations, expedited processing of a FOIA request is warranted if the request involves “circumstances in which the lack of expedited treatment could reasonably be expected to pose an imminent threat to the life or physical safety of an individual,” 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(1)(i), or “an urgency to inform the public about an actual or alleged federal government activity, if made by a person primarily engaged in disseminating information,” 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(l)(ii).  Requesters seeking expedited processing must submit a statement explaining in detail the basis for the request, and that statement must be certified by the requester to be true and correct.  6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(3). 

Your request for expedited processing is denied because you do not qualify for either category under 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(1).  You failed to demonstrate a particular urgency to inform the public about the government activity involved in the request beyond the public’s right to know about government activity generally.  Your letter was conclusory in nature and did not present any facts to justify a grant of expedited processing under the applicable standards. 

After thoroughly reviewing your letter and request for fee waiver, I have determined that you have not presented a convincing argument that you and/or your organization is entitled to a blanket waiver of applicable fees. 

The DHS FOIA Regulations at 6 CFR § 5.11(k)(2) set forth six factors to examine in determining whether the applicable legal standard for a fee waiver has been met.  We will consider these factors in our evaluation of your request for a fee waiver: 

(1) Whether the subject of the requested records concerns “the operations or activities of the government”; 
(2) Whether the disclosure is “likely to contribute” to an understanding of government operations or activities; 
(3) Whether disclosure of the requested information will contribute to the understanding of the public at large, as opposed to the individual understanding of the requestor or a narrow segment of interested persons; 
(4) Whether the contribution to public understanding of government operations or activities will be "significant"; 
(5) Whether the requester has a commercial interest that would be furthered by the requested disclosure; and 
(6) Whether the magnitude of any identified commercial interest to the requestor is sufficiently large in comparison with the public interest in disclosure, that disclosure is primarily in the commercial interest of the requestor. 

As a requester, you bear the burden under FOIA of showing that the fee waiver requirements have been met.  Based on my review of your 3/13/2025 letter and for the reasons stated herein, I have determined that your fee waiver request is deficient because your request did not satisfy factors 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6. Since your request for a fee waiver has failed to satisfy each of the required factors, I am denying your fee waiver request. 

Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations, as they apply to media requesters.  As a media requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. 

If you deem the decision to deny expedited treatment and fee waiver for your request an adverse determination, you have the right to appeal.  Should you wish to do so, you must send your appeal and a copy of this letter, within 90 days of the date of this letter following the procedures outlined in the DHS FOIA regulations at 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(e)(2). You may submit your appeal electronically at GILDFOIAAppeals@ice.dhs.gov or via regular mail to: 

U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Office of the Principal Legal Advisor 
U.S. Department of Homeland Security 
500 12th Street,, S.W., Mail Stop 5900 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5900 

Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

ICE has queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request. 

If you have any questions please contact FOIA Public Liaison Daniel Edgington, at (866) 633-1182 or 500 12th St, SW Stop 5009 Washington, DC 20536-5009. Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448. 

Your request has been assigned reference number 2025-ICFO-25068. Please use this number in future correspondence. 

Sincerely, 

ICE FOIA Office 
Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Freedom of Information Act Office 
500 12th Street, S.W., Stop 5009 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5009

Dear Requester: 

This letter is the final response to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), dated 3/13/2025.  You have requested records pertaining to a copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Jaspar Singh, who died in ICE Custody April 15, 2024, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddrSinghJaspar.pdf. ICE has considered your request under the FOIA, 5 U.S.C. § 552. 

ICE considered the foreseeable harm standard when reviewing the record set and has applied the FOIA exemptions as required by the statute and the Attorney General’s Guidance. 

A search of the ICE Offices of Enforcement and Removal Operations (ERO) and Office of Professional Responsibility (OPR) for records responsive to your request produced 8 pages that are responsive to your request.  After review of those documents, I have determined portions of 8 pages will be withheld pursuant to Exemptions of the FOIA as described below. 
ICE has applied FOIA Exemptions 6 and 7(C) to protect from disclosure the names, e-mail addresses, and phone numbers of DHS employees, as well as other third-party information contained within the documents. 

FOIA Exemption 6 exempts from disclosure personnel or medical files and similar files the release of which would cause a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy.  This requires a balancing of the public’s right to disclosure against the individual’s right to privacy.  The privacy interests of the individuals in the records you have requested outweigh any minimal public interest in disclosure of the information.  Any private interest you may have in that information does not factor into the aforementioned balancing test. 

FOIA Exemption 7(C) protects records or information compiled for law enforcement purposes that could reasonably be expected to constitute an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy.  This exemption takes particular note of the strong interests of individuals, whether they are suspects, witnesses, or investigators, in not being unwarrantably associated with alleged criminal activity.  That interest extends to persons who are not only the subjects of the investigation, but those who may have their privacy invaded by having their identities and information about them revealed in connection with an investigation.  Based upon the traditional recognition of strong privacy interest in law enforcement records, categorical withholding of information that identifies third parties in law enforcement records is ordinarily appropriate.  As such, I have determined that the privacy interest in the identities of individuals in the records you have requested clearly outweigh any minimal public interest in disclosure of the information.  Please note that any private interest you may have in that information does not factor into this determination. 

You have a right to appeal the above withholding determination.  Should you wish to do so, you must send your appeal and a copy of this letter, within 90 days of the date of this letter following the procedures outlined in the DHS FOIA regulations at 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.8. You may submit your appeal electronically at GILDFOIAAppeals@ice.dhs.gov or via regular mail to: 

U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Office of the Principal Legal Advisor 
U.S. Department of Homeland Security 
500 12th Street, S.W., Mail Stop 5900 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5900 

Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

Provisions of FOIA allow DHS to charge for processing fees, up to $25, unless you seek a waiver of fees.  In this instance, because the cost is below the $25 minimum, there is no charge. 

If you have any questions, please contact FOIA Public Liaison Daniel Edgington at (866) 633-1182 or 500 12th St., SW Stop 5009 Washington, DC 20536-5009.  Additionally, you have a right to right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448. 

Sincerely, 

Megan Davis 
Deputy FOIA Officer, Operations 

Enclosure(s):	8 Pages

Greetings, 

This communication is in response to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request, dated July 22, 2025. Please advise if you are willing to accept CLEARLY RELEASABLE documents. Clearly releasable meaning that we will apply any applicable FOIA exemptions to the documents before releasing them. 

In addition, please advise if you will accept the conformed copy of the contract. The conformed copy of the contract is the copy that incorporates all the modifications into one contract. 

Kindly respond by July 25, 2025 (3 business days), by the close of business so I can proceed with your request. 

Respectfully, 

Michael Maurice 
FOIA Coordinator 
NAVSUP Fleet Logistics Center Norfolk

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #2025-NavyFOIA-009500
communications.communication:
Hi Michael, thank you for the response. 

Can you please clarify what clearly releasable means? If it simply means redacting non-FOIA-able material within the requested documents then yes, that is acceptable. If you could include a redaction log referencing why aspects of the document were redacted I would appreciate it (just under what reason/code).  

A conformed copy of the contract is acceptable. Thank you.

Best,
Shawn

communications.subject: Clearly releasable clarification
communications.communication:
Good morning, 

In reference to your portal message about what clearly releasable would be, you are correct that we would redact any information which would fall within the applicable FOIA exemptions. 

In addition, there may be certain documents that are wholly exempt under a FOIA exemption and are not to be released at all. 

There would be an explanation in your final disposition letter explaining what exemptions were applied and the reasoning behind those exemptions. 

Please advise if you are still willing to accept clearly releasable documents with these parameters. 

I would also like to clarify what documents you are asking for when you ask for "all other contracting documents". The conformed copy of the contract will have the original contract, the SOW/PWS as well as all of the modifications through the most recent modification. Will that conformed copy of the contract suffice for what you are looking for in "all other contracting documents"? I don't want there to be any confusion or for you to not get what you are expecting. 

Please respond by July 31, 2025 (3 business days) so that I can proceed with your request. 

R, 

Mike Maurice

communications.subject: Final Disposition Letter 2025-NavyFOIA-009500
communications.communication:
Greetings, 

This communication is in response to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request, assigned tracking number 2025-NavyFOIA-009500, originally dated July 22, 2025, and then perfected on July 31, 2025, for the following information: 

“All contracting documents relating to TrapWire Inc (FPDS.gov Agency: 9700 Procurement Identifier: N0018924P0143). Please include the following documents: 

1) NDAs, MSAs, Statement of Work (SOWs), Invoices to-date (January 1, 2025 to the date of fulfilment), and other contracting documents between your agency and Trapwire Inc or parent company ABRAXAS APPLICATIONS, INC.” 

In response to your request, the following document is hereby being provided in its entirety: 

(1)	Contract: N0018924P0143 (28 pages) 

The foregoing document is provided with redactions pursuant to the following: 

FOIA Exemption 4 (5 U.S.C. §552(b)(4)), exempting disclosure of confidential business/source selection information. 

FOIA Exemption 6 (5 U.S.C. §552(b)(6)), exempting disclosure of names and other personally identifiable information pertaining to third parties in order to protect personal privacy. 

1.	I have concluded that releasing third-party privacy information of the type contained in the enclosed documents would clearly be an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy and could lead to harassment and embarrassment for the person(s) involved. 

2.	I have determined that releasing commercial and financial information of the type contained in the enclosed documents would have a detrimental effect on future government acquisition efforts by discouraging submitters of such information from voluntarily furnishing useful commercial or financial information to the government and correspondingly impact the assurance the government gets that the information will be reliable. 

I was advised that there are no NDA’s, MSA’s or invoices associated with this contract. 

Your document has been uploaded to Secure Release for you to view and download. If you have not done so already, please navigate to https://www.securerelease.us/ and create your account so that you can access the system. All future requests should be made through this system, and all documents will be released through this system. 

The fee associated with processing this request has been waived. If you have any questions, please contact me via e-mail at michael.j.maurice.civ@us.navy.mil. 

You have the right to an appeal. It must be received (i.e., post-marked if by mail, sent if by email, submitted if through the Internet) within 90 calendar days from the date of this letter. Please provide the appellate authority (see below) the following in an envelope marked “FOIA appeal”: 
•	a letter requesting an appeal that explains what you are appealing with any supporting arguments or reasons you think may be worthy of consideration. 
•	a copy of your initial request. 
•	a copy of the letter of denial. 

Also, please provide just a copy of your appeal letter: 

ATTN: FOIA Officer 
Naval Supply Systems Command (SUP03) 
5450 Carlisle Pike, BLDG 309-303-15 
Mechanicsburg, PA 17055-0791 

If by email to michael.j.maurice.civ@.us.navy.mil. 

The two main ways to file an appeal are by mail or through the Internet. 

1. By mail. Address your appeal to: 

The Judge Advocate General (Code 14) 1322 Patterson Avenue SE, Suite 3000, Washington Navy Yard, DC 20374-5066 

[Note: the preceding address is the default address. Alternatively, it may be sent to the Department of the Navy General Counsel if appropriate (the Office of the General Counsel generally handles issues outside of those of the uniformed service). That address is as follows: 

Department of the Navy, 
Office of the General Counsel, 1000 Navy Pentagon, Room 5A532 Washington, DC 20350-1000] 

2. Through the Internet. Use the public portal of the SecureRelease (the Department of the Navy's FOIA processing system). Go to https://www.securerelease.us.  Click "Login/Create Account" (in the top-right corner) and enter the information in the boxes that appear to create an account. Once that is done, you will be able to file an appeal for any request created through the SecureRelease portal by clicking the Create Appeal button in the top-right corner of the Request page. 
3. By email. The Judge Advocate General (Code 14) may be reached at Navy-OJAG-C14-FOIA-PA-ADMINAPPEALS@us.navy.mil. 

To appeal a request that was not submitted through the SecureRelease portal, create a SecureRelease portal account, then use the Create Request button on the SecureRelease portal homepage to create a FOIA request. In the Request Description field for that FOIA request, indicate that this is an appeal and make reference to the tracking number you have received for the request you wish to appeal. 

If you have any questions, please contact the FOIA coordinator at michael.j.maurice.civ@.us.navy.mil. You may also contact the DON FOIA Public Liaison, Christopher Julka, at christopher.a.julka.civ@us.navy.mil, (703)697-0031.  In addition, the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) provides a voluntary mediation process for resolving disputes between persons making FOIA requests and the Department of the Navy (DON).  For more information, go to https://www.archives.gov/ogis/mediation-program. 

Respectfully, 

Michael Maurice 
FOIA Coordinator 
NAVSUP FLC Norfolk

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jacob Silverman

Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 122 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 1,230 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 2,010 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,370 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.
